In this example, we can see a basic example of strategy in arranging your atoms to tasks.
- The front and two sides of the molecule are packed with defensive atoms.
The back is left vulnerable. If you want to keep a molecule quick and light, you can
strategically place the armor based on where you think it'll take the most damage.
- The middle front reveals the tip of the iceberg of attacking atoms. In core gameplay,
atoms cannot shoot through one another. Thus, a piece of the 'weapon' must be exposed.
Hiding the rest behind armor is a good strategy to keep it from taking damage in combat.
- The atoms providing thrust are in three groups. The middle one provides the most
centralized thrust, while the outer two allow for mobility and rotation to the molecule.
- There are two power plants, or energy producing groupings of atoms. Each one is adjacent
to all of the other groupings of the molecule.
- Roles are combined in powers of 2. In the 22 advancment model of core, groupings get an
additional boost to effects when they reach 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64 and so on atoms.
Arrangements of these sizes are typically the most effective in terms of use of mass, time,
and energy.

Atoms may also be adapted to work better in particular territories.
This allows certain regions of a map to provide a bonus to the atoms
'adapted' to its conditions. Absolute bonds must be between atoms
of the same color, and atoms must be in an environment to adapt to it.

This example demonstrates the use of absolute bonds in groupings that boost the
effectivesness of the atoms.
- Absolute bonds allow atoms to share everything. They are treated nearly as one.
- Absolute bonds must form with adjacent atoms on one of six (6) sides.
- Atoms must be assigned the same roles for an absolute bond to form. The bond
allows for more effective cooperation, like an infrastructure designed to handle
a specific task.
- It takes more time and energy to build and destroy absolute bonds than any other.
- For the 22 advancment model of core, groupings of 2, 4, and 8 are most effective.

This example demonstrates the use of energetic bonds to distribute power amongst
the different groupings of the molecule.
- Energetic bonds allow atoms to share energy between different groupings.
- The power plants of the molecule are positioned and built to provide a large
surface area for energetic bonds to form.
- Energetic bonds can reach across other atoms, and extend further than absolute
bonds. However, their effectiveness decreases drastically over distance.
- Some bonds are more important than others, and some are replicated. The
energetic bond connecting both power plants shares energy in case one becomes
less effective than another.

Molecule Example: Thief v0.0.1
Magnetic bonds work two ways. They either attract or repell in order to keep
two atoms at a distance with each other. They don't need to expend energy
to keep an atom in one spot, if no other forces are acting on it.
This is just one example of the use of magnetic bonds. In the event a typically
mobile unit has been attacked and lost their primary source of thrust, another
molecule can drag it to safety.
These can also be used on your enemies in core.
